WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.897
How do you glue loose desert sand into a solid crust?

2
00:00:02.997 --> 00:00:05.385
You grow the glue in place, out of thin air.

3
00:00:06.066 --> 00:00:10.248
An engineered enzyme called carbonic anhydrase captures carbon dioxide

4
00:00:10.348 --> 00:00:13.124
and, in water, converts it into carbonate ions.

5
00:00:15.700 --> 00:00:18.705
Meanwhile the sand supplies calcium. Positive calcium

6
00:00:18.805 --> 00:00:21.634
and negative carbonate attract, and lock together.

7
00:00:23.433 --> 00:00:27.306
Once the water is over-saturated — when this ratio climbs above one

8
00:00:27.406 --> 00:00:31.457
— the calcium carbonate can no longer stay dissolved. It crystallises.

9
00:00:32.733 --> 00:00:35.032
The fresh crystals grow at the contact points

10
00:00:35.132 --> 00:00:37.857
between grains, bridging them into one cemented mass.

11
00:00:38.833 --> 00:00:41.265
But there is a twist most models ignore. This

12
00:00:41.365 --> 00:00:44.247
enzyme route does not make hard limestone right away.

13
00:00:44.347 --> 00:00:47.510
It first makes a softer, unstable crystal called vaterite.

14
00:00:47.600 --> 00:00:52.091
Over the following hours vaterite slowly rearranges into strong, durable calcite

15
00:00:52.191 --> 00:00:55.362
— so the crust literally keeps getting harder as it ages.

16
00:00:55.433 --> 00:00:58.616
And because each carbonate came from carbon dioxide, every

17
00:00:58.716 --> 00:01:01.785
gram of crust also captures a little climate co-benefit.

